comments.text:
Scams under Indian National Congress governance:

We all know that Congress government was famous for scams. I would appreciate if someone shed some light on them. Thanks.

Major Major scams under INC:

Bofors Scam: The Bofors scam looks like a trademark of scams and corruption in India. This scam in 1980s involved the then Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, Hindujas and many other powerful names. The scam was about winning a bid to provide India with 155 mm field howitzers. The scam was related to the Indian defense and security, so was of much concern.
2G Spectrum Scam (2008): One of the biggest scams in India was the 2G scam, in which telecom minister A. Raja was charged for issuing 2G licenses to private telecom players at very cheap rates in 2008. No rules and regulations were followed but only favoritism was preferred while issuing the license. The scam cost Rs 1.76 lakh crore to the government. The government kept the entry fee for spectrum license at 2001 prices. Licenses was also issued to the companies with no prior experience in telecom. The mobile subscriber base in India touched 350 million in 2008 from 4 million in 2001.
Satyam Scam (2009): Indian investors and shareholders were badly affected by the scam involving Satyam Computer Services. The Satyam Scam involved Rs. 14,000 crore and was one of the biggest scams in the corporate world. Former Chairman Ramalinga Raju was involved in the scam, who kept everything under cover. He later confessed of falsifying the companys accounts by US $1.47 billion. Later in the year, 46% share of Satyam was bought by Tech Mahindra, who absorbed and revived the company.
Commonwealth Games Scam (2010): A huge amount of money for preparing and conducting the Commonwealth Games India was misused in the Commonwealth Games Scam. The total worth of Commonwealth Games Scam is estimated to be Rs. 70,000 crore. Again, many Indian politicians, bureaucrats and corporate bigwigs were involved in the scam. The face of the scam was Suresh Kalmadi, the Congress party representative to the 15th Lok Sabha from the Pune constituency. At that time, Kalmadi was the Chairman of the Organising Committee of the Delhi Commonwealth Games. Other big-shots involved were Sheila Dikshit, the then chief minister of Delhi and Robert Vadra. The payments were made to non-existent parties and prices were inflated while purchasing equipment, execution was delayed, and so on.
Coal Scam (2012): With the Coal Scam, the government bore a loss of Rs 1.86 lakh crore. The CAG presented a report and stated the irregularities involved in the auctioning of 194 coal blocks. The government decided not to auction coal blocks between 2004 and 2011. The coal blocks were then sold to different parties and private companies. This decision led to huge loss in terms of revenue.
Chopper Scam (2012): This scam is an example of bribery and corruption in India which involved many politicians, senior officials in India like former Indian Air Force Chief Air Chief Marshal S.P. Tyagi, and helicopter manufacturer Augusta Westland. The company had given bribe to get a contract for supplying 12 helicopters worth USD 610 million. A note presented on March 15, 2008 in an Italian court indicates that the Congress President Sonia Gandhi was also involved in the scam.
Tatra truck scam (2012): The case against Vectra Chairman Ravi Rishiformer and Army Chief Gen. V.K. Singh had been registered by the Enforecement Directorate under the Prevention of Money Laundering Act (PMLA). The scam involved a sum of Rs. 14 crore as bribe. The bribe was given to make way for purchasing 1,676 Tatra trucks for the Army.
Adarsh Scam (2012): The Adarsh Housing Scam is related to the allocation of flats below market rates in a very posh 31-storey building, the Adarsh Housing Society in Colaba, Mumbai. The society was made for war widows and personnel of Indias Ministry of Defence. Over a period of time, rules and regulation were modified for the allocation of flats. Allegations have been made against three former chief ministers of Maharashtra  Sushilkumar Shinde, Vilasrao Deshmukh and Ashok Chavan. Also, the land belonged to the defence and had been given for the society.
The list of scams under Congress UPA government is too long and looks never-ending. A few more in the list are Telgi scam, Insurance scam, Telecom scam (Sukh Ram), Fodder scam, Ketan Parekh scandal, Taj corridor case, Oil-for-food programme scam, Bombay Stock Exchange Fraud, Madhu Koda, and money laundering worth Rs. 4000 Crs.

comments.text:
Below is a list of alleged scams associated with Narendra Modi and the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), as claimed by various opposition parties, media reports, and public discourse. Note that some of these are allegations that remain unproven or are under investigation, while others have been legally contested or dismissed. Ill present them one by one as requested, based on available information up to March 21, 2025, without reproducing copyrighted material or fabricating details:

1. *Rafale Deal Controversy*  
   - **Allegation**: Critics, notably the Congress party, claimed irregularities in the 2016 purchase of 36 Rafale fighter jets from France, alleging that the deal favored industrialist Anil Ambanis Reliance Defence through inflated costs (estimated at 59,000 crore).  
   - **Status**: The Supreme Court of India dismissed the plea for a probe in 2018, finding no evidence of wrongdoing. However, a French investigation into possible corruption continues as of recent reports.

2. *Electoral Bonds Scheme*  
   - **Allegation**: Introduced in 2018, this scheme allowed anonymous donations to political parties. Critics allege it facilitated corruption, with the BJP receiving the lions share (over 6,986 crore as per some estimates). Opposition parties called it a legalized scam for quid pro quo deals.  
   - **Status**: The Supreme Court declared the scheme unconstitutional in February 2024, citing transparency issues, but no definitive proof of a "scam" has been established.

3. *Punjab National Bank (PNB) Scam*  
   - **Allegation**: In 2018, jeweler Nirav Modi and his uncle Mehul Choksi defrauded PNB of 14,000 crore through fraudulent Letters of Undertaking. Critics blame the Modi government for lax oversight of public sector banks.  
   - **Status**: The scam predates Modis tenure in some aspects (starting in 2011), but it surfaced under his watch. The accused fled India; recovery efforts are ongoing.

4. *Vyapam Scam (Madhya Pradesh)*  
   - **Allegation**: A massive recruitment and admission scandal in Madhya Pradesh under BJP Chief Minister Shivraj Singh Chouhan, involving irregularities in exams and jobs, with estimates of financial losses in thousands of crores. Its also linked to mysterious deaths of whistleblowers.  
   - **Status**: Investigations have been criticized as inadequate, with no conclusive conviction of top BJP leaders as of now.

5. *Belekeri Ore Scam (Karnataka)*  
   - **Allegation**: During the BJPs rule in Karnataka (20082013), illegal iron ore exports worth over 12,000 crore were reported, implicating leaders like B.S. Yediyurappa and G. Janardhana Reddy.  
   - **Status**: Probes were initiated, but key figures faced limited legal consequences, with allegations of political interference.

6. *Gujarat State Petroleum Corporation (GSPC) Scam*  
   - **Allegation**: During Modis tenure as Gujarat CM, GSPC allegedly mismanaged funds, incurring losses of 20,000 crore due to failed gas exploration projects. Congress claimed it was a cover for financial irregularities.  
   - **Status**: The Comptroller and Auditor General (CAG) criticized the project, but no criminal charges were proven against Modi or BJP leaders.

7. *Jay Shah Controversy*  
   - **Allegation**: In 2017, a report alleged that Amit Shahs son Jay Shahs company saw a 16,000-fold profit increase (80 crore turnover) after Modi came to power, hinting at cronyism.  
   - **Status**: Jay Shah filed a defamation case, and courts found no evidence of a scam. The allegations remain unproven.

8. *Demonetisation (2016)*  
   - **Allegation**: Critics, including Congress, labeled the sudden withdrawal of 500 and 1,000 notes a "scam," alleging it benefited BJP allies and failed to curb black money, with hidden motives to favor certain corporates.  
   - **Status**: No concrete evidence supports this as a scam; its largely a policy critique.

9. *Karnataka COVID-19 PPE Scam*  
   - **Allegation**: During the pandemic, the BJP government in Karnataka was accused of overpaying for PPE kits and mismanaging funds, though exact amounts remain unclear.  
   - **Status**: Investigations are ongoing, with opposition alleging cover-ups.

10. *Ayushman Bharat Fraud*  
    - **Allegation**: Reports of fake beneficiaries and hospitals siphoning off funds (estimated at 1,000 crore in some states) under this healthcare scheme have surfaced, with critics pointing to poor oversight by the Modi government.  
    - **Status**: State-level actions have been taken, but no direct link to BJP leadership has been proven.

11. *Pradhan Mantri Awas Yojana (PMAY) Fund Scam*  
    - **Allegation**: Alleged diversion of housing scheme funds in states like Uttar Pradesh and Gujarat, with unspecified amounts misappropriated by local officials.  
    - **Status**: Investigations are ongoing at the state level, with no national-level BJP culpability established.

12. *Adani Group Allegations*  
    - **Allegation**: Post a 2023 Hindenburg Research report, the Adani Group was accused of stock manipulation and accounting fraud, with opposition linking it to Modis perceived closeness to Gautam Adani. Losses were pegged at $150 billion in market value.  
    - **Status**: Modi has not commented extensively; no direct evidence ties the government to a scam.

13. *Lalit Modi Controversy*  
    - **Allegation**: In 2015, former IPL chief Lalit Modi, a fugitive, allegedly received help from BJP leaders like Sushma Swaraj and Vasundhara Raje, sparking claims of favoritism.  
    - **Status**: No formal charges were proven against BJP leaders.

14. *Chhattisgarh PDS Scam*  
    - **Allegation**: A 36,000 crore rice distribution scam under CM Raman Singhs tenure was flagged by Congress, alleging corruption in the Public Distribution System.  
    - **Status**: Investigations stalled, with no convictions of top leaders.

This list reflects allegations commonly cited by critics. Many cases lack final judicial verdicts, and the BJP often counters that these are politically motivated claims lacking substance. For the latest updates or deeper details on any specific case, further research or a specific query would be needed!
